<h2>Storm Karine</h2>
<br><br>
Storm Karine moved over the Iberian Peninsula, the southern part of France and the northern part of Italy on the 2nd of March and was soon followed by storm Myriam on the 3rd of March, which followed almost the same track. The storms followed a long series of storms in Europe in February, caused by a positive NAO Index, i.e. a large pressure gradient between the north and south of the Atlantic Ocean, causing a strong westerly wind.
Storm Karine developed rapidly in a deep trough belonging to a low pressure system near Scotland.
<br><br>
The storm spreaded rain, gusty winds and some high-elevation snow from Portugal to France.
<br><br>
Aemet, the Spanish State Meteorological Agency, reported wind gusts of 120-150 km/h in large parts of northeastern Spain, and a highest wind gust of 176 km/h in Valdezcaray (La Rioja). In the Mediterranean Sea between Catalonia and the Baleares, waves of 4-5 meter were reported. The Pyrenees experienced more than 60 mm precipitation in 24 hours. M&#233;t&#233;o-France reported wind gusts around 130 km/h in the the Hautes-Pyr&#233;n&#233;es and Haute-Garonnes. In the village Orleix 25 houses lost their roofs due to strong winds.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/mar2020/SoC2020_03_fig1.png"><img alt="" src="../images/mar2020/SoC2020_03_fig1.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1. Analysis of 2 March 06 UTC with low pressure system Karine located over the south of France. (Source: KNMI)</em>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/mar2020/SoC2020_03_fig2.png"><img alt="" src="../images/mar2020/SoC2020_03_fig2.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2. Storm Karine developed in a deep trough along the jet stream. (Source: Aemet)</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for March 2020</h2>
After the storm Karine, a high-pressure area was established which resulted in a persistent anti-cyclonic flow with fair weather. In central Europe about twenty cold nights (figure 3, left) occured, which was above the 1981-2010 average (figure 3, right). Due to subsidence, the cloud cover was low (figure 13), leading to strong radiative cooling at night time, low minimum temperatures, and a pronounced daily temperature cycle.
<br><br>
